\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Determinants of the Gender Gap in Productivity and Gross Revenue from Maize in Eastern Uganda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Emma Prati
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This study investigates gender differences in maize productivity and gross sales revenue in Eastern Uganda.
 Using a mixed-methods approach,
 the analysis combines quantitative and qualitative data with a focus on male and female headed households in the Busoga region.
 First,
 ordinary least squares models are estimated to descriptively examine gender gaps across productivity and gross revenue from maize.
 Both baseline and pooled panel data covering three rounds of data collection are used.
 Following that,
 the Oaxaca-Blinder decomposition technique is employed at baseline to decompose gender gaps in productivity and gross revenue from maize into differences in endowments and differences in returns to those endowments.
 The focus group discussions complement econometric analysis by giving contextual information about gendered dynamics in maize production in the Busoga region.
 The findings show that female-headed households have lower maize productivity and substantially lower maize revenue than male-headed households.
 The decomposition results suggest that these gaps are only partly explained by differences in observable characteristics,
 while unequal returns to these resources and structural constraints constitute key components of the gap.
 Qualitatively,
 we found that these gaps are shaped by time constraints,
 technologies adoption,
 market dynamics and gendered control over maize-related resources.
 The results imply that reducing these gaps will require policies that go beyond equalizing productive resources and also address the structural constraints faced by female-headed households.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Sub-Saharan Africa,
 agriculture remains a key driver of economic activity and a primary source of employment,
 particularly in rural areas.
 In Uganda,
 the population is predominantly rural and relies substantially on agriculture (FAO,
 2024).
 The following analysis focuses on the cultivation of maize,
 one of the most important staple crops in Ugandan agriculture.
 In this context,
 understanding underlying causes behind low agricultural performance becomes essential for food security.
 Despite that,
 progress has remained particularly slow,
 with productivity growth lagging well behind other regions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Suri2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is the reason why increasing agricultural productivity and raising incomes of rural households is one of the goals of Uganda's Agriculture Sector Development Strategy and Investment Plan (DSIP),
 which aims to improve food security and nutrition for all Ugandans (De La O Campos et al.,
 2015).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this regard,
 one of the most persistent and costly inefficiencies is the gender gap in agricultural productivity (Buehren,
 2023).
 Although their contribution varies substantially across countries and farming systems,
 women constitute a substantial share of the agricultural labor force in Sub-Saharan Africa that goes over 55% in Uganda
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Palacios-López02092015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Despite that,
 women tend to achieve lower yields in comparison to their male counterparts (Mukasa,
 2015).
 A large body of literature shows that women in agriculture in Sub-Saharan Africa face persistent institutional and structural constraints,
 including a limited access to land and productive inputs,
 markets,
 credit and labour,
 as well as time constraints linked to household and care-giving responsibilities,
 that prevent them from achieving productivity levels comparable to those of men (Duflo & Udry,
 2004,
 Peterman et al.,
 2010,
 Kilic et al.,
 2015;
 Palacios-López & Lopez,
 2015;
 Ali et al.,
 2016).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the gender gap in agricultural productivity,
 the agricultural sales revenues are also not distributed evenly.
 Despite agricultural income differ geographically,
 female-headed households remain among the poorest of the poor (Djurfeldt,
 2013).
 The literature shows that the unequal access to productive inputs and strong discriminatory barriers contribute to enhancing gender gaps in income from farm activities (Kinkingninhoun-Mêdagbé et al.,
 2010;
 Dandonougbo et al.,
 2023;
 Mkuna & Wale,
 2023).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
