\begin_layout Plain Layout
Another key constraint for female- headed households' agricultural productivity and income is the widespread under-adoption of modern agricultural technologies,
 such as improved seed varieties,
 fertilizers,
 and pesticides (source).
 Despite input mechanization expanding especially in maize production (Williamson,
 2008,
 more recent),
 adoption remains gendered with male-headed households being more likely to use modern inputs (Peterman et al.,
 2010;
 Sheahan & Barrett,
 2017).
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
However,
 existing evidence suggests that lower adoption rates among female farmers are often driven not by a lower willingness to adopt,
 but by differential access to the information and resources required to use these technologies effectively (Peterman et al.,
 2010)
\end_layout

\end_inset

Understanding adoption of modern maize seed varieties is important not only because it affects productivity and income,
 but also because it can cause and perpetuate gender gaps.
 (remove maybe?)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper contributes to the bulk of evidence on gender differentials in agricultural maize productivity and gross revenue by analyzing household-level panel data from 3,500 smallholder maize cultivating households in Busoga region,
 in Eastern Uganda.
 I estimate baseline and pooled OLS models and apply Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition to assess the relative contribution of differences in endowments versus structural differences in returns to these endowments in determining productivity and gross revenues gaps from maize between male headed households (MHH) and female-headed households (FHH).
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Furthermore,
 the analysis quantifies the impact of adoption of improved maize seed varieties on productivity and income gaps between female and male headeded households.
 To address the potential endogeneity of adoption decisions,
 an instrumental variables (IV) strategy was used to estimate the causal impact of adopting improved seed on maize productivity and income for female-headed households and male-headed households.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In parallel,
 we conducted a qualitative analysis consisting of 16 focus group discussions with smallholder farmers in the same region.
 This mixed-methods approach provide a comprehensive understanding of gendered constraints in agricultural production.
 The paper provides policy relevant evidence on the factors underlying the differences in agricultural outcomes between MHH and FHH cultivating maize.
 Understanding these gender differentiated constraints is essential for achieving an inclusive agricultural transformation,
 improving welfare and food security.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results show that female-headed households achieve significantly lower maize productivity and revenue than male-headed households,
 and that these gaps persist even after accounting for observable differences in household and plot characteristics.
 The Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition indicates that unequal returns to resources,
 rather than unequal access to them,
 account for the majority of both gaps.
 The qualitative evidence points to time constraints ,
 technology adoption and gendered market discrimination as key mechanisms underlying these structural disparities.
\end_layout

