\begin_layout Section
Theoretical Framework and Hypotesis 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:2-Theoretical-Framework and Hypotesis-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Understanding why male-headed (MHH) and female-headed households (FHH) achieve different outcomes in maize production requires distinguishing between two separate sources of inequality:
 unequal access to productive resources and unequal returns to those same resources.
 This distinction,
 formalized in the labour economics literature as the division between endowment and structural components (Oaxaca,
 1973;
 Blinder,
 1973),
 serves as the initial basis for the analysis underlying this study.
 Insights from the focus group discussions (presented in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Qualitative-Evidence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) also contributed to the development of the theoretical framework and the formulation of the hypotheses presented in this chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gender gaps are measured by comparing MHH and FHH outcomes.
 To clarify what being a female-headed household actually entails,
 the literature distinguishes between de jure FHH,
 in which women are permanently without a male partner due to widowhood,
 divorce,
 or separation,
 and de facto FHH,
 in which the male partner is temporarily absent,
 typically because of labour migration,
 but may continue to contribute economically through remittances (Raney et al.,
 2011).
 In Uganda,
 the large majority of FHH are de jure,
 meaning that in most cases there is no male partner contributing labour,
 income,
 or negotiating capacity to the household (Raney et al.,
 2011).
 For this reason,
 I draw on Whitehead’s (1981) concept of the conjugal contract.
 Whitehead shows that husbands and wives do not necessarily pool their labour and income into a single,
 jointly managed household economy.
 Instead,
 they may operate under an implicit contract,
 with separate obligations,
 roles,
 and claims over decisions,
 all mediated through the marital relationship.
 Therefore,
 I assume the absence of a partner to have important consequences for FHH,
 which lack a household member socialized into the roles commonly assigned to men within many MHH.
 In Feminist Africa,
 Tsikata (2009) further develops the concept of conjugal contract in the context of African agrarian and informal economies.
 She argues that women often combine agricultural work with their role of caregiver,
 childcare and household duties,
 but the time and attention taken away from farming are completely invisible and not captured by standard agricultural productivity covariates.
 Palacios-López and López (2015) provide an economic explanation of how these differences may affect agricultural outcomes.
 Following their model,
 households are assumed to have the same preferences and to derive utility from income 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and leisure 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(Y,l;Z_{hh})=Y+u(l)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{h}$
\end_inset

 represents a vector of exogenous household characteristics.
 The household allocates its total time endowment,
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

,
 between leisure 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

,
 on-farm labour 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{f}$
\end_inset

 and off-farm labour,
\begin_inset Formula $L_{o}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=l+L_{f}+g(L_{o})
\]

\end_inset

with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(L_{o})=\alpha_{o}+\alpha_{1}L_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(L_{0})$
\end_inset

 captures the effective time cost of off-farm work.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
 represents fixed costs,
 such as travelling to work,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
 captures the time cost of each additional unit of off-farm labour.
 Palacios-López and López (2015) claim that this cost may be higher for women because they combine income-generating activities with unpaid activities such as childcare and domestic responsibilities assigned to them through social expectations and the conjugal contract previously discussed,
 reducing the time available for agricultural and income-generating activities (Palacios-López et al.,
 2015;
 Pierotti et al.,
 2022;
 Buehren,
 2023).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model also assumes that households with limited access to credit may rely on off-farm earnings to finance agricultural inputs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
rX\leq\gamma+wL_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $rX$
\end_inset

 is expenditure on agricultural inputs,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 represents available credit or initial financial resources,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $wL$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
 is off-farm income.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This mechanism may affect productivity through several channels.
 A higher time cost of off-farm work can reduce both the income available to purchase productive inputs and the time available for agricultural production.
 As a result,
 FHH may face stronger labour and liquidity constraints than MHH,
 which can lead to lower agricultural productivity even when some observed inputs are similar.
 This argument complements Whitehead’s concept of the conjugal contract and provides an economic formulation of Tsikata’s argument that women’s unpaid domestic and care work reduces the time and attention available for productive activities.
 Therefore,
 in this study,
 these constraints are expected to be particularly important for FHH,
 especially de jure FHH.
 Taken together,
 these theories provide the basis for expecting a productivity gap between MHH and FHH (H1) and for expecting this gap to persist after controlling for observable endowments (H2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same constraints may also affect gross sales revenue through two channels.
 First,
 lower access to labour,
 liquidity,
 and agricultural inputs may reduce productivity and the quantity of maize available for sale.
 Therefore,
 MHH are expected to achieve higher gross sales revenue than FHH (H3).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second,
 the gender norms and roles previously discussed may limit women’s education,
 mobility,
 access to information,
 participation in farmer networks,
 and experience in market transactions.
 These disadvantages may be particularly important for de jure FHH,
 which cannot rely on a male partner to provide market information,
 contacts,
 or bargaining support.
 As a result,
 FHH may be less likely to participate in maize markets and may face weaker bargaining positions when they sell.
 Building on the analysis of Mekonnen et al.
 (2018),
 Dickinson and Koo (2022) argue that unequal access to information,
 technology,
 and education may limit women’s ability to identify profitable selling opportunities,
 obtain favourable prices and weaken their bargaining power,
 restricting their ability to increase agricultural earnings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although originally developed in the context of labour markets,
 Becker’s theory of taste-based discrimination provides an additional lens through which to interpret gendered treatment in maize markets.
 The theory suggests that market actors may treat individuals differently because of preferences or social stigma.
 The theory is complemented by the statistical discrimination models developed by Phelps (1972) and Arrow (1973),
 suggesting that,
 when knowledge or reliability cannot be perfectly observed,
 market actors may use group identity as a proxy,
 including characteristics such as race and sex.
 Although these theories were originally developed in labour economics,
 their logic can also apply to agricultural market transactions.
 Buyers may use gender as a proxy for limited market knowledge or bargaining capacity and may therefore treat women selling independently differently.
 This may affect whether FHH participates in the market,
 the terms under which they sell,
 and the prices they receive.
 It may also expose them to lower offers and manipulated scales.
 These mechanisms provide the basis for expecting a gap in gross sales revenue between MHH and FHH (H3) and for expecting this gap to persist after accounting for observable endowments,
 with the structural component exceeding the endowment component (H4).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on this theoretical framework,
 the study tests the following hypotheses:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
H1:
 MHH are more productive than FHH in maize cultivation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
H2:
 The gender gap in maize productivity between MHH and FHH persists after controlling for observable endowments,
 and the structural component of the gap exceeds the endowment component.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
H3:
 MHH have higher gross sales revenue from maize than FHH.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
H4:
 The gender gap in maize gross sales revenue between MHH and FHH persists after accounting for observable endowments,
 and the structural component of the gap exceeds the endowment component.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Literature Review
\lang english

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec3 -Literature Review"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gender gaps in agricultural productivity and income are typically explained by two sources of inequality:
 unequal access to resources and unequal returns to those resources.
 A common approach to analyzing such gaps is the Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition of mean differences,
 a well-established empirical strategy in labor economics,
 originally developed by Oaxaca (1973) and Blinder (1973).
 The decomposition separates the mean difference into a component explained by observable characteristics (endowment effect) and a component reflecting the differences in returns to those characteristics (structural effect).
 Kilic,
 Palacios-López,
 and Goldstein (2015) were the first to apply this approach to the analysis of agricultural productivity and a growing number of studies followed (Palacios-López and Lopez,
 2015;
 Slavchevska ,
 2015;
 Ali et al.,
 2016;
 Bello et al.,
 2021).
 Extending this framework,
 we employ the Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition to examine gender gaps in both agricultural productivity and gross sales revenue from maize production.
 The existing literature indicates that both unequal endowments and structural constraints contribute to gender gaps in agricultural productivity,
 although their relative importance varies across contexts (Buehren,
 2023).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A first strand of this literature finds that most of the observed gender gap in agricultural productivity is explained by unequal access to productive resources,
 highlighting the key importance of access to inputs in observed yields differentials (Kilic et al.,
 2015;
 De la O Campos et al.,
 2016).
 For example,
 De la O Campos et al.
 (2016) demonstrate that the gender gap in agricultural productivity in Uganda diminishes once differences in access to production factors,
 such as fertilizers and pesticides,
 are taken into account,
 with the endowment effect explaining between 58% and 96% of the gap,
 depending on the gender indicator used.
 Similarly,
 Kilic et al.
 (2015) finds that 82% of the average gender productivity gap is explained by differences in observable characteristics,
 mainly high-value crop cultivation and the availability of adult male household labour.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Some studies even find an endowment advantage of women (Ali et al,
 2015;
 Oseni et al.,
 2016)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 other studies find that important differences in agricultural productivity persist even after equalizing for input access,
 identifying returns to inputs as the main contributors of the gender gap in agricultural productivity (Aguilar et al.,
 2014;
 Slavchevska,
 2015;
 Ali et al.,
 2016).
 Focusing on Uganda,
 Ali et al.
 (2016) finds a stronger structural component through the decomposition,
 driven mostly by a male structural advantage.
 Of the total gap the study identifies that two fifths of the gender gap in productivity are explained by unequal returns to the child dependency ratio (Ali et al.,
 2016).
 Similarly,
 Aguilar et al.
 (2014) finds that in Ethiopia a higher structural component that amount to 57.6% of the total gap.
 The gap is largely driven by non-married female managers,
 especially divorced women and it is mainly driven by (Aguilar et al.,
 2014).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gender gap in agricultural productivity,
 particularly in maize production,
 usually translates into a gender gap in sales,
 as documented by Buehren (2023),
 thereby reinforcing processes of feminization of poverty.
 Part of this revenue gap may simply reflect the underlying productivity gap or differences in access to productive inputs;
 however,
 the revenue also depends on whether and how much of the harvest is sold,
 and these could be subjected to structural barriers and disequalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some studies find that endowments constitute the main cause of gender gap in agricultural earnings.
 Mkuna and Wale (2023) records gender income gap of approximately 50% in cabbage farmers in South Africa and explain that differences in observable resources and endowments account for approximately 92% of the farm-income gap.
 They also relate this result to previous evidence that female-managed farms face substantial endowment disadvantages,
 particularly in farm size and in the use and intensity of non-labour inputs and agricultural services (Mukasa & Salami,
 2015).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other studies,
 point instead to a predominant role for structural differences in explaining gender gaps in agricultural earnings.
 Applying an Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition to maize market participation among male- and female-headed households in Ethiopia,
 Marenya et al.
 (2017) find that the gap in the probability of selling maize is driven primarily by structural rather than endowment factors,
 suggesting that market access itself,
 not just productivity,
 is a distinct source of gendered income disparities.
 Recent researches in Togo,
 suggests that the average agricultural farm income gap observed between men and women is about 66%,
 of that the two structural components jointly account for approximately 73% (Dandonougbo et al.,
 2023).
 Related evidence from southern Ethiopia also points to structural disadvantages in agricultural market participation:
 Gebre et al.
 (2021) find that significant gender gaps in maize market participation are strongly associated with differences in returns to resources rather than with endowment differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 while gender disparities in agricultural productivity have been extensively studied,
 evidence on gendered agricultural earnings differentials from farming in Africa remains limited and fragmented (Gebre et al.,
 2021;
 Mkuna & Wale,
 2023),
 particularly regarding the relative contribution of endowment and structural effects in maize production in Uganda.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although these contributions provide a meaningful overview,
 context-specific analysis is required to effectively guide policy recommendations.
 This paper contributes to this literature in two ways.
 First,
 while existing evidence largely relies on intra-household comparisons between male- and female-managed plots (Kilic et al.,
 2015;
 Ali et al.,
 2016),
 we compare male- and female-headed households directly,
 using household-level panel data on maize production in the Busoga region of Uganda.
 Second,
 we extend the analysis beyond productivity alone by jointly estimating gender gaps in productivity and gross sales revenue,
 combining decomposition methods with qualitative evidence to shed light on the mechanisms underlying these disparities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The literature shows that prevailing cultural norms and local systems of land access often disadvantage women,
 who rarely inherit land and instead cultivate plots borrowed from husbands or relatives,
 frequently consisting of smaller and lower-quality parcels;
 this pattern of gender-based marginalization in land allocation,
 both in terms of quantity and quality,
 has been widely documented in Sub-Saharan Africa (Basile,
 2001;
 Dey Abbas,
 1997;
 Saito et al.,
 1994;
 Palmer,
 1991;
 Lubbock,
 1988),
 suggesting that differences in endowments could play a key role in shaping different agricultural outcomes.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
While decomposition methods identify the relative contribution of observable characteristics and structural differences,
 they do not establish causal relationships.
 After presenting descriptive evidence,
 the paper examines the causal relationship between the adoption of hybrid maize seeds varieties and both maize productivity and gross farm income using an instrumental variables (IV) approach.
 Existing research on gender inequalities in access to agricultural technologies has largely focused on inorganic fertilizers,
 while evidence on improved seed adoption remains vague (Peterman et al.,
 2010).
 Doss and Morris (2001) find that once controlled for complementary inputs,
 differences in adoption rates between male and female farmers largely disappear.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
According to several studies,
 technology adoption represents one of the main channels through which differences in access to inputs translate into productivity and income disparities (source)
\end_layout

\end_inset

In contrast,
 other studies argue that even with similar access to modern inputs,
 women often obtain lower returns from their use (Tiruneh et al.,
 2001;
 Sanginga et al.,
 2007).
 Djurfeldt (2013) claims that the benefits of technology adoption depend not only on access to inputs but also on the ability to integrate into markets dynamics,
 highlighting the role of commercialization,
 access to markets and information.
 The weaknesses in agricultural credit markets further limit farmers’ ability to finance investments in improved inputs (Sheahan & Barrett,
 2017).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

