\begin_layout Subsection
Quantitative Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Quantitative Sample
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper uses panel data from three survey rounds with approximately 3,500 smallholder maize farmers in Busoga region.
 The data were originally collected within a broader research project examining agro-input dealers and farmer interactions in Uganda (De et al.,
 2024;
 Miehe et al.,
 2025,
 2026).
 The agro-dealer sample was constructed by listing all agro-dealers operating across eleven districts in the Busoga region,
 an area characterized by smallholder maize production,
 where maize serves both as a staple food and a cash crop.
 To link agro-dealers with farmers,
 each agro-dealer was asked to identify the villages where most of their customers reside.
 Enumerators then randomly sampled ten maize-growing households from each of these villages,
 yielding the sample of 3,470 farmers.
 The dataset also identifies the catchment area in which each household is located.
 Catchment areas represent the relevant local spatial units used in the decomposition analysis to account for shared characteristics among households located in the same area.
 Enumerators interviewed the household member most knowledgeable about maize cultivation.
 A subset of questions specifically targeted the household head,
 who may or may not have been the respondent.
 In addition to general information on agricultural practices,
 farmers were asked to list all their maize plots,
 from which one was randomly selected for detailed data collection.
 This approach minimized survey duration and respondent burden while preserving representativeness at the household level,
 due to the random selection of plots.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first round of data were collected in April 2021,
 followed by the second round of surveys in January-February 2022 and third round of surveys in July-August 2022.
 Of the 3,470 farmers interviewed in the first round of data collection,
 3,407 were re-interviewed at second one and 3,441 at the third round.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Measurement of Key Outcome Variables and Covariates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis focuses on two main outcome variables:
 productivity and gross sales revenues from maize.
 All variables are measured on the randomly selected plot.
 Agricultural productivity is measured as maize yield per unit of cultivated land,
 capturing differences in output across plots.
 Maize gross revenue is measured as the gross value of maize sales,
 expressed in Ugandan shillings.
 For households that did not sell maize,
 income is set to zero.
 For households that reported selling maize,
 income is calculated as the quantity sold multiplied by the unit price received.
 The resulting measure therefore captures both the extensive margin of market participation and the intensive margin of sales among participating households.
 Observations with missing information on sold quantities or bag prices among sellers are left as missing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hybrid seeds adoption is measured as a binary indicator equal to one if the household reports using one of the officially recognized hybrid maize varieties (Longe 10H,
 Longe 7H,
 Longe 7R Kayongo-go,
 Bazooka,
 Longe 6H,
 Panner,
 Wema,
 or KH series) on the randomly selected plot during the reference season,
 and zero otherwise.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the skewed distribution and the presence of zero values in the outcome variables,
 maize productivity and gross sales revenues are transformed using the inverse hyperbolic sine (IHS) transformation in the empirical analysis.
 Skewness is according to the adjusted Fisher-Pearson coefficient of skewness exceeding 1.96.
 To address the recent critiques by Mullahy and Norton (2022) we applied the IHS transformation cautiously when dealing with outcome variables that have many zeros and impacts on the extensive margin.
 For larger values of the outcomes,
 the IHS behaves similarly to a logarithmic transformation,
 although percentage interpretations should be treated as approximates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distribution of maize productivity was inspected to identify potentially influential observations arising from unusually high reported harvests relative to plot area.
 Small plot areas can mechanically increase measured productivity and amplify measurement error.
 However,
 most extreme productivity observations are driven primarily by unusually high reported harvest quantities,
 rather than by a generalized presence of very small plot areas.
 Since these observations are internally consistent with the original survey responses and have only a small influence on the gender gap in IHS-transformed productivity,
 they are retained in the main analysis and excluded only in a robustness check in the appendix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gross maize sales revenue is highly right-skewed.
 The unconditional mean gap decreases when observations with extreme reported prices are excluded,
 indicating that the raw mean is partly influenced by a small number of high revenue observations among male-headed households.
 However,
 the corresponding gap in IHS-transformed revenue changes only marginally,
 suggesting that the econometric results are unlikely to be driven by these observations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main covariates analysed in the dataset cover access to agricultural inputs markets,
 household demographic and socioeconomic characteristics,
 farm and land endowments,
 plot-level input use and management practices,
 maize sales.
 These covariates were selected based on the literature (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec3 -Literature Review"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 as well as their availability in the dataset.
 They capture key observable factors that may influence maize productivity and gross sales revenue.
 However,
 the analysis cannot account for all relevant factors,
 including soil quality and weather conditions.
 These omitted factors may contribute to the unexplained component of the Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition,
 which should therefore not be interpreted as discrimination alone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The descriptive statistics reported in table 
