\begin_layout Subsubsection
Empirical Issues 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Oaxaca Blinder decomposition relies on a set of identifying assumptions (Fortin et al.,
 2011).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aggregate decomposition is valid under the assumption of overlapping support,
 which requires sufficient similarity in the distribution of observable characteristics across male and female headed households.
 This condition was carefully assessed by inspecting the distribution of key covariates across male and female headed households.
 The Kernel density plots (reported in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Distribution-of-IHS-transformed"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Results"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) indicate substantial overlap in the main covariates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The detailed decomposition additionally depends on the assumptions of additive linearity (Fortin et al.,
 2011).
 Additive linearity assumes that the outcome can be expressed as a linear combination of observed covariates.
 In our setting,
 the specification tests do not indicate major functional form problems,
 indicating that a linear model provide a reasonable description of the outcomes.
 Functional-form concerns might be relevant for maize revenue because of the large mass at zero and its strongly right-skewed distribution.
 RESET tests and alternative income specifications are therefore used as diagnostic checks and included in the Appendix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The credibility of the decomposition also relies on the plausibility of the ignorability and zero conditional mean assumptions.
 Ignorability requires that,
 conditional on the observed covariates,
 the gender of the household head is not correlated with unobserved factors affecting productivity and income.
 The zero conditional mean assumption requires that the error term is not systematically correlated with the included covariates.
 While these assumption cannot be tested directly (Fortin et al.,
 2011),
 the specification incorporates a rich set of household and plot-level characteristics widely used in the literature (Kinkingninhoun-Mêdagbé et al.,
 2010;
 Peterman et al.
 2010;
 Palacios-López & López,
 2015;
 Wayagi et al.,
 2025) thereby reducing the scope for omitted variable bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although panel-data extensions of the Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition have been used in other settings (Slavchevska,
 2015;
 Ali et al.,
 2016),
 the main decomposition in this study is implemented on the baseline cross-section because the baseline survey contains the richest and most consistently measured set of household covariates.
 Midline and endline observations are used in pooled OLS specifications,
 but they are not used for the main Oaxaca decomposition because several key endowment variables are not consistently re-measured across rounds.
 Carrying baseline covariates forward is acceptable in pooled OLS as a way to control for relatively stable household characteristics,
 but it is less appropriate in an Oaxaca decomposition because these covariates directly determine the endowment component.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As stated previously,
 since decomposition techniques rely on correlations,
 they cannot be understood as estimates of causal parameters (Fortin et al.,
 2011).
 However,
 these methods can record the relative quantitative significance of components in explaining an observed gap,
 indicating priority for additional research and policy actions (Kilic et al.,
 2015).
 Given that the objective of the analysis is descriptive rather than causal,
 the detailed decomposition results are interpreted with caution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A further empirical issue concerns the distribution of maize income,
 which exhibits a substantial mass at zero because a sizeable share of households report no maize sales during the reference period.
 As a result,
 the income outcome combines market participation (whether any maize is sold) and sales intensity/earnings conditional on participating.
 At baseline,
 48.8 percent of households report zero maize income.
 This share is substantially higher among female-headed households,
 60.5 percent,
 than among male-headed households,
 45.3 percent.
 Therefore,
 the maize income outcome captures both the probability of selling maize and the amount earned conditional on selling.
 Missing information on quantity sold or price among sellers is very limited,
 affecting only seven observations.
 The main concern in the income variable is therefore the large share of zero sales and the strong right-skewness of positive income values.
 Consequently,
 the Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition of maize income should be interpreted as a decomposition of overall maize commercialization income rather than of earnings among sellers only.
 It reflects both differences in market participation and differences in sales intensity conditional on participation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The econometric findings are complemented by qualitative evidence,
 which helps contextualize gendered differences in agricultural production,
 supporting the interpretation of the decomposition results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Qualitative Analytical Approach 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Qualitative data were analyzed using a thematic coding approach aimed at identifying recurring patterns related to gendered constraints in maize production and commercialization.
 Qualitative data were coded using the analysis software package ATLAS.ti,
 which facilitated systematic data organization.
 A deductive coding structure was developed based on the interviews questions and the study’s analytical focus,
 while remaining open to inductive coding during the analysis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The final coding structure included themes related to bargaining power,
 decision-making over inputs and income,
 labor allocation,
 market access,
 technology adoption,
 time constraints,
 and gender norms and roles
\end_layout

\end_inset

We allowed the overlapping of the codes to reflect the interconnected nature of the themes and particular attention was paid to patterns of co-occurrence across codes.
 The results are presented in the subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Qualitative-Evidence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Discussion-and-Limitations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Selected excerpts were used to illustrate the main themes and support the interpretation of the quantitative results.
\end_layout

