\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "descriptive statistics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 presents baseline descriptive statistics separately for MHH and FHH.
 For each variable,
 the table reports the mean,
 minimum,
 maximum,
 standard deviation,
 and number of non-missing observations for each group.
 The final column reports the difference in means between MHH and FHH,
 together with significance levels from two-sided t-tests of equality of means.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The table covers access to agricultural inputs markets,
 household demographic and socioeconomic characteristics,
 farm and land endowments,
 plot-level input use and management practices,
 maize sales,
 and the two main outcome variables:
 productivity and gross sales revenue from maize.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several baseline characteristics differ significantly between MHH and FHH.
 The formers are usually slightly larger households,
 with an average of 8.85 members compared with 8.15 members in FHH.
 MHH are also slightly younger,
 averaging 48.3 years compared with 49.7 years among female heads,
 and they are considerably more likely to have completed primary education,
 at 56% compared with 34%.
 The largest demographic difference concerns marital status:
 98% of male household heads are married,
 compared with 56% of female household heads.
 This pattern is consistent with the definition of FHH discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:2-Theoretical-Framework and Hypotesis-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 in which female headship is often linked to the absence of a male spouse.
 The table also shows consistent differences in land endowments.
 MHH cultivate an average of 3.53 acres,
 compared with 2.70 acres among female-headed households.
 They also cultivate slightly more maize plots,
 1.48 compared with 1.40,
 and the randomly selected maize plot is larger among male-headed households,
 averaging 1.23 acres compared with 1.01 acres.
 All three differences are statistically significant,
 already indicating land endowments advantages between MHH.
 Differences in input use are more mixed.
 MHH are more likely to use quality seed (51% compared with 42%) and urea fertilizer (42% compared with 38%),
 and they weed the selected plot more frequently.
 By contrast,
 FHH report slightly higher use of DAP/NPK fertilizer (9% compared with 7%),
 while no significant differences emerge for hybrid seed,
 pesticides,
 or organic manure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regarding the outcome variables,
 already from the descriptive statistics,
 it is possible to observe that significant differences are present both in in maize productivity and gross revenue from maize sales between MHH and FHH.
 Productivity is higher for MHH,
 both in standard units (kg/acre) and when using the IHS transformation.
 Similarly,
 gross revenue from maize shows a statistically significant difference in levels and IHS terms,
 favoring MHH.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Distribution-of-IHS-transformed"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 complements these comparisons of mean outcomes by showing the full distributions of IHS-transformed maize productivity and gross sales revenue through Kernel density estimates.
 Although substantial overlap exists between MHH and FHH,
 the distributions for MHH are shifted toward higher values,
 particularly for gross sales revenue.
\end_layout

