6.2.2 OLS - Gross Sales Revenue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:OLS-estimates-of-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports analogous results for maize sales revenue derived from the randomly selected plot.
 The raw revenue gap in Column (1) is large and statistically significant,
 with MHH earning substantially 1.016 IHS
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Because gross sales revenue includes zero values for non-selling households,
 the IHS coefficient is reported in transformed units rather than converted into a percentage.
 The outcome combines market participation and the value of sales among sellers.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 units higher maize gross revenue than FHH.
 Once controls are introduced (Column 2),
 the estimated gender gap declines but remains economically large and statistically significant,
 indicating that differences in plot size,
 input use,
 and household characteristics explain only part of the observed income disparity.
 Plot size,
 measured in logarithmic terms,
 emerges as a key determinant of maize gross revenue.
 Input use plays an important role in shaping income outcomes.
 The use of quality seeds,
 fertilizers,
 and chemical inputs is positively associated with maize gross revenue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 gender-specific regressions reveal heterogeneity in returns across different inputs.
 While urea application is significantly associated with higher maize income among FHH,
 chemical inputs are significant only among MHH suggesting that returns to specific inputs differ by gender rather than being uniformly higher for one group.
 As we have noticed with productivity,
 education of the household is positively associated with maize income among FHH.
 Household characteristics also matter.
 The household size and the age of the household head are negatively associated with gross revenue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results from the pooled gross revenue specification indicate that the gender gap in gross sales revenue income persists in the pooled bigger sample,
 with the estimated gender coefficient remaining positive and statistically significant.
 Plot size remains positively and statistically significant in the pooled specification,
 confirming that scale effects continue to play an important role in explaining differences in maize revenue across households over time.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If I add productivity:
 In both specifications,
 as expected,
 higher maize productivity is associated with higher income from maize,
 confirming the central role of agricultural performance in determining gross revenue.
 However,
 substantial gender disparities persist even after conditioning on productivity.
 This suggests that gross revenue gender disparities may be influenced by other factors beyond production.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although comparing raw and controlled specifications shows the extent to which observable factors contribute to the gender gap,
 this empirical technique does not identify the underlying mechanisms that drive differences between male and female headed households.
 The different returns observed across the regressions motivate an explicit decomposition of the gap which we undertake in the following section using the Oaxaca–Blinder framework.
\end_layout

