\begin_layout Plain Layout
Table 4 summarizes the factors influencing the adoption of improved maize seed varieties.
 In the raw specification (Column 1),
 male-headed households had a considerably higher likelihood of adoption.
 However,
 the effect disappears when household and plot-level characteristics are controlled for,
 suggesting that the gender differences in adoption are largely explained by unequal access to resources and inputs.
 These results are consistent with previous studies showing that once differences in access to inputs such as land,
 education and inputs are accounted for,
 gender itself does not significantly affect adoption of improved seeds (Doss,
 2001;
 Horrell & Krishnan,
 2007).
 The use of agricultural inputs,
 particularly DAP/NPK fertilizer,
 Urea,
 and chemicals,
 is positively and significantly associated with adoption both at baseline and in the pooled models,
 indicating that hybrid seeds are adopted as part of a broader input use.
 Education also increases the probability of adoption,
 with a stronger effect among female-headed households
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
,
 confirming the findings of Anang (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 There is also a significant association between membership in a farmer group or cooperative and adoption both for female and male headed households.
 Being part of a farmer organization increases the probability of using hybrid seeds,
 likely reflecting improved access to information,
 markets that reduce uncertainty surrounding new technologies.
 As stated in section 4,
 as a robustness check,
 we estimate logit models for hybrid seed adoption.
 The results,
 reported in the Appendix,
 are consistent with the linear probability model.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Oaxaca-Blinder Decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Oaxaca-Blinder Decomposition - Productivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tables 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Twofold-aggregate-decomposition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Detailed-twofold-decomposition-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 report the twofold and threefold Oaxaca–Blinder decompositions of the gender gaps in maize productivity
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since the gender gap is defined as the mean productivity of male-headed households minus that of female-headed households,
 positive values indicate higher average outcomes among male-headed households.
 The same accounts for gross revenue.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Confirming the OLS estimates the decomposition indicates a maize productivity gap of 0.197 IHS units,
 suggesting that on average female-headed households have about 20% lower maize productivity compared to male-headed households.
 The twofold decomposition shows that 0.051 IHS units,
 corresponding to 26.2 % of the productivity gap,
 are explained by observable differences in endowments.
 The remaining 0.145 IHS units,
 or 73.8 % of the gap is attributed to differences in returns to these characteristics,
 suggesting that gender disparities in maize productivity are driven primarily by structural factors,
 differential returns to inputs,
 and gender-specific constraints rather than by unequal access to resources alone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The threefold decomposition further separates the coefficient component into male and female coefficient components.
 The male coefficient component is 0.032 IHS units (≈22%),
 and the female coefficient component is 0.114 IHS units (≈78%).
 Both coefficient components contribute positively to the productivity gap,
 with the female coefficient component accounting for the larger share of the coefficient effect.
 This indicates that the productivity gap is not only associated with differences in observed characteristics,
 but also with the way these characteristics translate into productivity for female-headed households relative to the pooled benchmark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The additive linearity property explained in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Empirical Strategy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

makes it possible to assess the relative contribution of each production factor to both the endowment and structural effect through the detailed decompositions of productivity reported in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Detailed-twofold-decomposition-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 These detailed contributions are not causal effects of individual covariates;
 rather,
 they show how differences in observable characteristics and differences in estimated coefficient structures contribute mechanically to the overall gap.
 From table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Detailed-twofold-decomposition-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

education contributes positively and significantly to the endowment component,
 indicating that differences in education levels widen the productivity gap.
 However,
 the coefficient component for education is negative,
 suggesting that differences in the education-productivity relationship reduce rather than widen the gap.
 This is consistent with the OLS models,
 where education has a stronger positive association with productivity among FHH.
 Urea application shows a similar pattern:
 its endowment contribution is close to zero,
 while its coefficient component is negative and statistically significant.
 This suggests that differences in the coefficient structure associated with urea application reduce rather than amplify productivity disparities.
 Overall,
 through the detailed decomposition the productivity gap appears to reflect a combination of small endowment differences and differences in coefficient structures.
 Other covariates are not significant.
\end_layout

