\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.3.2 Oaxaca-Blinder Decomposition - Gross Sales Revenue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tables 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Twofold-aggregate-decomposition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Detailed-twofold-decomposition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 report the twofold and threefold Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition of the gender gaps in maize gross revenue.
 As visible in previous results,
 the total gap here is substantially larger than the productivity gap.
 The estimated gross revenue gap of 0.711 corresponds to nearly 97% lower maize gross revenue among female-headed households relative to male-headed households.
 A sizable share of this gap (≈ 41%) is explained by differences in observable characteristics.
 Nevertheless,
 about 59% of the gross revenue gap is associated with differences in the coefficient structure.
 Compared with productivity,
 observable endowments explain a larger share of the gross revenue gap,
 suggesting that differences in plot area,
 input use,
 and other household and farm characteristics play an important role in shaping gross revenue disparities.
 Nevertheless,
 more than half of the gross revenue gap remains associated with coefficient differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The threefold gross revenue decomposition show that the male coefficient component amounts to 0.093 IHS units (≈ 22% of the total coefficient component),
 while the female coefficient component amounts to 0.331 IHS units (≈ 78%).
 As in the productivity decomposition,
 the female coefficient component represents the largest part of the coefficient effect.
 This pattern suggests that gross revenue disparities may be related not only to differences in productive resources,
 but also to gendered differences in the ability to convert those resources into monetary returns.
 However,
 because maize gross revenue contains many zero observations,
 the gross revenue decomposition should be interpreted as reflecting both market participation and conditional earnings,
 rather than a single gross revenue generating process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The detailed decomposition,
 reported in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Detailed-twofold-decomposition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 shows a clearer role for observable endowments.
 Plot area is the largest positive contributor to the explained component,
 indicating that differences in cultivated area account for an important part of the gross revenue gap.
 Education plays a dual role in the gross revenue decomposition.
 On the one hand,
 the positive endowment component indicates that differences in educational attainment contribute to widening the gross revenue gap.
 On the other hand,
 the coefficient components associated with education are negative and statistically significant,
 suggesting that differences in the estimated returns to education reduce the gap.
 This pattern is consistent with the gender-specific OLS results,
 where education appears more strongly associated with maize gross revenue among female-headed households.
 Surprisingly,
 the household size has a negative and statistically significant endowment contribution,
 indicating that differences in household size reduce rather than widen the gross revenue gap.
 By contrast,
 the coefficient component for the age of the household head is large,
 positive,
 and statistically significant,
 suggesting that differences in the age-gross revenue relationship contribute to widening the gap.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall,
 the decomposition results indicate that gender gaps in gross revenue are only partly explained by observable differences in household and farm characteristics and a strong component of the gap remain structural.
\end_layout

