\begin_layout Subsection
Qualitative Evidence 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Qualitative-Evidence"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The qualitative results are organized around four analytical areas which correspond to the main mechanisms shaping the gender gap in the analysed outcomes that emerged during the discussion:
 social norms and labor division;
 decision making processes;
 technology adoption and community perception;
 market dynamics.
 As explained in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Data-and-Context"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the contribution where from women-only,
 male-only and mixed focus group discussion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gendered time use and labour division
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Across all focus groups,
 gender norms emerged as a key determinant of labour allocation and time use among maize farmers.
 Both female and male participants consistently described a fixed and rigid division of labour,
 with farming roles framed as natural and socially prescribed.
 As one participant stated,
 “the roles of men are men’s and the ones for women are women’s” (men-only FGD).
 Male participants in particular described women as physically weaker and only suitable for lighter agricultural activities,
 such as planting,
 weeding,
 harvesting,
 while agricultural tasks requiring physical strength or technical judgment,
 like slashing and spraying,
 were explicitly associated with men:
 “Women are weak and can only manage weeding while the man can do everything” (men-only FGD).
 However,
 some female participants challenged this narrative emphasizing substantial changes over time.
 Particularly in women-only focus groups,
 women repeatedly stressed that they now take care of a wide range of agricultural activities traditionally associated with men.
 As one participant explained,
 “Nowadays even the women prepare land,
 burn grass and even slash” (women-only FGD),
 while another added “what a man can do even the woman can do” (mixed FGD).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Across focus groups,
 women were widely associated with childcare and domestic responsibilities,
 often working alongside children in the fields.
 As one female participant noted,
 “I and the children are the ones who work most because since we are done with his garden then he has not time at all to step on the joint garden (\SpecialChar ldots
) He returns in the night when you are done working” (women-only FGD).
 Women’s agricultural labour remains closely tied to care-giving roles,
 even as they increasingly take on tasks previously considered male and rather than replacing existing domestic responsibilities,
 it was added on top of them,
 leading to widespread time poverty and limiting agricultural productivity.
 Women described delayed arrival to maize plots,
 shorter working hours,
 and early departure due to household obligations.
 These qualitative insights suggest that social constraints limit women's time and labour division and could contribute to gender gaps in maize productivity and gross revenue.
 These constraints may be particularly significant for FHH,
 where husbands are generally absent or less involved in daily farming and household activities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite this heavy workload,
 women repeatedly portrayed these tasks as unavoidable,
 framing them as natural and inherent to being a woman.
 As one participant explained,
 “God prepared us as women that you cannot leave home without sweeping the house,
 have not cleaned the compound and the kitchen” (women-only FGD).
 Similarly,
 women across different focus groups emphasized the inevitability of these roles:
 “I see they do affect me but still I have no choice” (mixed FGD),
 and “those roles are naturally mine and I have to do them whether I want to or do not want to” (mixed FGD).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While some men,
 particularly in mixed focus groups,
 acknowledged domestic work as labour,
 others framed household and childcare responsibilities as a way for women to avoid agricultural work.
 Male focus groups highlighted their own productivity in the fields while portraying women’s care activities as avoidable disruptions:
 “they want us to have equal share of things but they are lazy (\SpecialChar ldots
) and tend to cheat us in that way,
 you may be digging the fourth or fifth row and yet she will do only three rows and say she is heading back home,
 I am going to prepare home” (mixed FGD).
 These perceptions were directly linked to agricultural outcomes,
 with participants concluding that “This leads to poor farm management and low yields” (mixed FGD).
 Consistent with this framing,
 male participants often interpreted women’s childcare responsibilities,
 such as breastfeeding,
 not as binding constraints but as excuses for rest or reduced effort.
 As one man put it,
 “When she holds the baby she will be using it as an excuse to sit (\SpecialChar ldots
) It helps her to just sit there and rest” (men-only FGD).
 In more than one women-only interview,
 we observed that women’s time constraints extend beyond agricultural and domestic labour to include expectations of sexual availability,
 revealing how gender norms structure both productive work and bodily autonomy:
 “By the time you leave the garden then you cook and then bath the children and then you find that you leave the garden when you are tired and eat supper while tired and then go to bed when you are tired and then the man will start saying that I want to have sex.” (women-only FGD).
 Taken together,
 these accounts indicate that women’s agricultural work is carried out under substantial time and care constraints that are not directly measured in the quantitative data.
 The qualitative evidence on women’s time constraints and care responsibilities helps contextualize the differential returns component identified for FHH in the decomposition,
 as similar input levels may translate into lower effective supervision and productivity outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Decision-making and control over agricultural resources
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discussions with the smallholder farmers also suggest that gendered norms are also likely to assign rights over inputs and output independently of effort,
 contributing to an unbalanced decision making process.
 Across focus groups,
 decision-making over agricultural inputs and gross revenue from maize varied across plot types,
 between women-managed plots,
 jointly managed plots,
 and male-owned plots,
 reflecting gendered power relations within households.
 In male-owned plots,
 women’s contribution rarely translated into decision-making power and usually the man decides on inputs,
 sometimes after a joint discussion.
 In women-managed plots,
 women were generally described as having more autonomy over input decisions,
 including maize variety and fertilizer use.
 However,
 some male participants suggested that men retain decision-making authority even over women’s plots,
 often referring to the saying “omwami kyakobye” (“what the man says”).
 In jointly managed plots,
 decisions over inputs were more frequently described as either jointly discussed or male-led,
 with men often making the final decision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Income decisions followed similar patterns.
 Only-women focus groups stressed that men retain control over harvests despite limited labor contribution.
 In jointly managed plots,
 gross revenue from maize sales was often described as discussed within the household,
 yet men frequently had the final say.
 As one participant stated:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

My husband is the one who decides because there is no way you can decide for him though.
 It is not by law that he decides but it depends on how you relate and the togetherness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (women-only FGD).
 Along similar lines,
 some male participants stated that:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The household decisions are not made by a woman because it becomes a dead household
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

(men-only FGD) reflecting strict norms about male authority over gross revenue.
 In contrast,
 women more often reported control over gross revenue generated from plots they managed independently.
 Women’s control over maize gross revenue is sometimes justified through gendered moral narratives that frame women as more responsible household managers than men.
 They usually decide to have their own garden to be sure to have control over it and use the money for the family as decisions related to children’s expenses were consistently framed as women’s responsibility.
 Describing her garden a female participant claimed:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

with that I have the right to decide on my own and that since I have sold this maize let me give this to a certain child and also buy something for the household and for myself because you know as women we do not behave like the men that when they receive they go and get more wives.
 For us we prepare for the household well-being
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (women-only FGD).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These findings about decision-making process do not directly explain the gross revenue gap between MHH and FHH,
 but they show that household-level revenue does not necessarily indicate who controls or benefits from the proceeds,
 particularly within MHH.
 Additionally,
 they suggest that female headship may give women more direct control over farming and sales decisions,
 while women in MHH may contribute substantially without having the final say.
 However,
 greater decision-making autonomy in FHH does not necessarily imply greater access to the resources needed to implement those decisions or better agricultural outcomes,
 as evidence suggests that women who exercise visible autonomy may face suspicion or social disapproval from the wider community.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Technology adoption and social sanctions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Participants described the adoption of new technologies,
 such as hybrid seeds or fertilizers,
 as generating both admiration and suspicion in the community.
 While some people are recognized and respected for their productivity outcomes,
 others were viewed as envious and their success was often solely attributed to supernatural means.
 Throughout all focus groups,
 witchcraft was mentioned regularly when discussing individuals who achieved higher yields.
 As one participant explained,
 “we start to say that one is a ‘mukuluzi’—
the one who pulls all other people’s yields to his or her own garden” (women-only FGD),
 while another added that “they say the woman uses witchcraft to collect all the maize from the neighbor’s gardens” (mixed FGD).
 In particular,
 female headed households were sometimes portrayed as violating accepted gender roles when adopting new technology.
 As participants reported,
 “they say that woman is unmanageable,
 she is a woman who is a man” (men-only FGD),
 and “she is the one wearing the trouser,
 the man is wearing the skirt” (mixed FGD).
 In female-only discussions,
 women underlined that economic success may lead to social scrutiny for women,
 as village members often questioned whether a woman who earned substantial gross revenue through farming would remain manageable within the household (women-only FGD).
 Overall,
 social reputation and community moral judgment serve as informal constraints on technology adoption for both women and men,
 resulting in uneven diffusion across households.
 These narratives imply that technology adoption is viewed as a practice grounded in community norms,
 rather than a neutral technical choice.
 These informal social sanctions may therefore help contextualize both gender differences in access to and adoption of productive technologies and differences in the returns generated from similar endowments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Market dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Across focus groups,
 participants described a non-neutral market with unequal access,
 price-setting practices,
 and with women facing a higher risk of being cheated by maize buyers,
 even though some respondents reported that prices can be equal for men and women under certain conditions.
 Both men and women claimed that traders frequently abuse information asymmetries,
 especially when interacting with women,
 who are regarded to be less knowledgeable about current market values.
 As one participant noted,
 “there is a difference as women are cheated because they think women are not knowledgeable” (men-only FGD).
 Others linked this directly to mobility and access to information,
 stressing that men are believed to be more informed because “men listen to the radios and get latest price updates” (mixed male,
 FGD).
 Price discrimination was described not only in terms of lower offered prices,
 but through manipulation of weighing scales.
 Participants reported that similar maize bags could be weighed differently depending on the seller’s gender,
 resulting in systematic losses for women.
 Consequently,
 some men explicitly stated that women should not sell maize independently to avoid being cheated,
 as illustrated by one participant who explained,
 “my wife does not sell without me being around because I don’t want her to be cheated” (men-only FGD).
 These market dynamics may lead to structural gross revenue discrepancies between MHH and FHH,
 as maize sales in female-headed homes are typically handled by women,
 who are thus more vulnerable to gendered forms of price discrimination.
 In these circumstances,
 collective marketing via farming organizations and cooperatives was widely regarded as a technique for decreasing price discrimination and fraud.
 While some participants were wary about cooperatives,
 others emphasized that selling collectively allowed women and men to reach the same consumers,
 reducing knowledge gaps and limiting opportunistic behavior.
 As one participant explained,
 “that is why you see we want to all join groups,
 in a group they give you the same price—
the man and I the woman” (women-only FGD).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discussion and Conclusions 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Discussion-and-Limitations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study uses a mixed-methods approach to understand the gender gaps in maize productivity and gross sales revenue between male-headed households (MHH) and female-headed households (FHH) in the Busoga region of Eastern Uganda.
 Despite the extensive literature,
 there is still no consensus on whether gender gaps in agricultural outcomes are mainly driven by observable differences in resources and input use or by structural factors that remain after these characteristics are taken into account.
 Some studies find that the gap largely disappears after controlling for endowments access whereas others find that a substantial gap persists.
 Oseni et al.
 (2015) further demonstrate that the relative importance of the two components may vary considerably within the same country.
 This study revisits and expand this debate using mixed-methods evidence from Eastern Uganda.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regarding productivity,
 the raw OLS estimates show that MHH achieve higher outcomes in both areas.
 These gaps remain statistically significant after controlling for household characteristics,
 farm resources,
 and input use,
 and they also persist in the pooled estimates across survey rounds.
 For maize productivity,
 the raw estimates indicate that MHH achieve approximately 20% higher productivity than FHH(β=0.199).
 Despite using a different indicator,
 this result is consistent with De la O Campos et al.
 (2016),
 who report a difference in mean log productivity between plots managed by male and female headed households of 0.177,
 corresponding to a gap of approximately 19.4%.
 The results show that the gap decreases after controls but remains positive and statistically significant in the pooled estimates.
 These results support H1 and show that observable differences do not fully account for the lower productivity of FHH.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition of the productivity gap provides further support for H1 and H2:
 endowment differences explain about 22% of the productivity gap,
 while the coefficient component accounts for about 78%.
 This result is close to Aguilar et al.
 (2015),
 who find that the structural component explains 57.6% of the productivity gap in Ethiopia,
 and to Slavchevska (2015),
 who shows that observable characteristics partly offset a larger coefficient disadvantage in Tanzania.
 It contrasts with Kilic et al.
 (2015) and de la O Campos et al.
 (2016),
 who find that endowments explain most of the productivity gap in Malawi and Uganda.
 Part of this difference may come from the gender indicator used (De la O campos,
 2016).
 These studies often compare male- and female-managed plots,
 while this study compares MHH and FHH.
 Results may also vary with the set of covariates available.
 The detailed O-B decomposition shows that the coefficient component does not reflect lower estimated returns for FHH across every input.
 For instance,
 the lower education among FHH widens the productivity gap through the endowment component,
 but the coefficient contribution of education reduces the gap.
 This confirm the OLS estimates,
 where education is more strongly associated with productivity among FHH.
 As explained by Croppenstedt et al.
 (2013) education constitutes an important channel through which women access information,
 extension services,
 credit,
 and agricultural technologies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Qualitatively,
 focus-group findings provide useful context to understand the productivity gap.
 Women described combining farming with childcare,
 food preparation,
 and other domestic duties.
 They reported arriving later at the plot,
 leaving earlier,
 and having less time to supervise agricultural work.
 They also explained that they increasingly perform tasks traditionally assigned to men without giving up their existing household responsibilities.
 These findings are consistent with research on time poverty and care responsibilities in agriculture (Ali et al.,
 2016;
 Sell et al.,
 2018;
 Pierotti et al.,
 2022;
 Donald et al.,
 2023).
 They are also consistent with the mechanism formalized by Palacios-López and López (2015) discussed in the theoretical framework in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:2-Theoretical-Framework and Hypotesis-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The qualitative evidence points to constraints that are not captured by the survey variables and inform the analysis on the structural mechanism underlying the observed gap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results for gross revenue supports H3:
 the raw estimates indicate that MHH earn approximately 1.016 IHS units more gross sales revenue than FHH.
 The gap falls to about 0.633 after controls,
 but remains large and statistically significant.
 The pooled estimate also remains positive and significant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The O-B decomposition provides support for H4:
 endowments explain about 41% of the revenue gap,
 while the coefficient component accounts for about 59%.
 Endowments therefore matter more for revenue than for productivity,
 but they still do not explain the full gap.
 This result is consistent with Dandonougbo et al.
 (2023),
 Gebre et al.
 (2021),
 and Marenya et al.
 (2017),
 who also find an important role for coefficient differences in agricultural income and maize market participation.
 In fact,
 despite focusing on male and female plot owners,
 Dandonougbo et al.
 (2023) find that 58.5% of the average farm gross revenue gap in Togo is accounted for by structural advantages enjoyed by male farmers.
 Through the detailed decomposition we see that plot area is the main positive contributor to the revenue endowment component.
 FHH cultivate smaller plots,
 which limits the amount of maize available for sale.
 This is consistent with the findings of Mkuna and Wale (2023).
 Similarly to the effect on productivity,
 education widen the endowment gap but has negative coefficient contribution because it is more strongly associated with revenue among FHH in the separate OLS estimates.
 Quality-seed use,
 by contrast,
 contributes positively to both the endowment and coefficient components.
 Overall,
 the detailed results show several effects working in opposite directions rather than one uniform pattern of lower returns among FHH.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The focus-group evidence adds further context to the findings about revenue gap.
 The social stigma surrounding women’s technology adoption may discourage women from adopting investment in new technology and new inputs,
 such as new quality seeds.
 Moreover,
 participants reported that women often had less access to current price information and faced a higher risk of receiving lower offers and being cheated.
 This is consistent with studies showing that agricultural information often circulates through gendered networks that are more accessible to male farmers (Mekonnen et al.,
 2018;
 Mullally et al.,
 2022;
 Caldarola et al.,
 2022;
 Dickinson & Koo,
 2022).
 This is also consistent with the decomposition results,
 which show that education plays an important role in the revenue gap,
 particularly through differences in educational endowments between MHH and FHH.
 Participants also described the manipulation of weighing scales and the belief among buyers that women were easier to deceive.
 Some therefore preferred women to sell with a man present,
 which is particularly difficult for FHH without a resident male partner.
 The limited access together with women’s weak bargaining power,
 restrict their ability to increase agricultural earnings,
 and leave FHH with fewer alternative sources of income (Dickinson & Koo,
 2022).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall,
 the main findings support all four hypotheses.
 MHH achieves higher maize productivity and gross sales revenue than FHH,
 and both gaps remain after observable characteristics are taken into account.
 The coefficient component is larger for both outcomes in the main IHS specifications,
 although land,
 education,
 and input access remain important,
 especially for revenue.
 Improving women’s access to productive resources is therefore necessary,
 but it may not be sufficient.
 Policies should also address time constraints,
 access to information and unequal treatment in maize markets.
 Education stood out as a powerful tool to diminish both gaps thanks to the high returns on both productivity and revenue.
 The combined quantitative and qualitative evidence supports the broader argument developed in the theoretical framework:
 gender gaps depend not only on which resources households possess,
 but also on the social conditions under which FHH can access,
 use,
 and benefit from those resources.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Given the substantial benefits of modern agricultural technologies,
 this study addresses a high-impact research area.
 While both men and women face adoption challenges,
 our focus is on understanding constraints specific to female farmers.
 The project will generate actionable evidence to enhance technology uptake among female smallholders in sub-Saharan Africa,
 a critical step toward building resilience in a vulnerable population.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
8 Limitations and Future Research
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:8-Limitations-and"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The study advances the literature by giving new context-specific evidence on potential gender-differentiated outcomes in smallholder maize farming.
 The findings have policy implications for equitable productivity and gross revenue outcomes in maize production in Eastern Uganda.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The benchmark in the threefold decomposition:
 the allocation of the coefficient component into male and female coefficient components is sensitive to the choice of benchmark.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Interesting to look at the distribution (RIF):
 Although Aguilar et al.
 find that more than half of the productivity gap is related to structural issues,
 age and years of schooling are significant effects only at the higher levels of productivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Choice of indicator:
 As highlighted in the literature,
 aggregate decomposition results vary across crops and contexts,
 and the relative contribution of endowment and structural effects depends on how gender is conceptualized,
 whether in terms of household heads,
 plot holders,
 or farm managers (De la O Campos et al.,
 2016).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Unobserved data not computed in the equation,
 such as agro-ecological conditions may emain captured in the returns component (Fortin et al.,
 2011).
 But also the endowments could be generated by structural disequalities.
\end_layout

